On February 15, 2021 Dogecoin was valued at $0.058444 (Coindesk). In the past month, the Dogecoin value has dropped by about 3.5%. There has not been one day in March where the end-of-day value for Dogecoin was more than $0.051. With 1 week left until the deadline, it does not seem likely that Dogecoin value will pass $0.058.

The markets are in a bit of turmoil with the COVID relief bill in flux. March 15th is the day after legislation is expected to pass. The final language of the bill will impact the market, but the one day will most likely not be enough time to bring it back up to the February 15th price. However, predictions for Dogecoin are that the average price will be $0.06 in April 2021.

The end-of-day price on Feb 15th was the result of a spike following the spread of doge-related investment memes on popular subreddits [1]. Like any meme, it will die with time. Additionally, the price of Dogecoin has plummeted since its height, with its value being cut into a third of what it once was as lucky investors sell and late investors panic-sell. Due to the lack of popular momentum, I suspect that Dogecoin will continue to plummet in value and will most likely not reach its former height of price as seen on February 15th.

It seems that established investors and advisors, such as Charlie Munger, are coming out as quite critical of Bitcoin in general, and lots of decision makers listen when guys like Charlie speak in such ways regarding these matters. While I doubt it will impact its popularity in any way, I do believe that it is more volatile to predict as any number of celebrities - such as Elon Musk or Snoop Dogg - can tweet their support at any time for Dogecoin, thus prompting a rally.

Crypto is a speculative asset. Crypto is climbing now along with the stock market because of all of the loose money created by the Federal Reserve. Crypto is not a hedge against the stock market like gold. When the stock market takes a hit, crypto tends to decline as well. I am pessimistic on the price of Doge because I am pessimistic on the economy over the next month, specifically due to rising inflation and rising treasury rates.
